    "remark": "The lesson is that in induction the base case is not a formality but the load-bearing wall: the step here propagates the entire one-parameter family $\\tan^{-1}\\!\\frac{m}{m+1}$, so the value of the sum is decided solely by where you nail it down. The bait is that $\\cot^{-1}$ is defined at $0$ — $\\cot^{-1}0=\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$ is a real principal value, not a hole — which makes an unwarranted $k=0$ term look admissible and silently adds $\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$ to every partial sum, swapping the true limit $\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}$ for the plausible $\\tfrac{3\\pi}{4}$. The telescoping and complex-argument views make the honest anchor unmistakable: the first genuine boundary contribution is $-\\tan^{-1}1$, not $\\arg i$. Recognising which terms an index actually contains is the whole game."
