          "Let $S_n=\\sum_{k=1}^{n}\\tan^{-1}\\frac1{F_{2k+1}}$. Using the verified even-index telescope, $S_n=\\tan^{-1}1-\\tan^{-1}\\frac1{F_{2n+2}}$. Compute its tangent by the subtraction formula (legitimate as $S_n\\in(0,\\tfrac{\\pi}{4})$ for all $n$, since it is an increasing sum bounded by the limit): $\\tan S_n=\\dfrac{1-\\frac1{F_{2n+2}}}{1+\\frac1{F_{2n+2}}}=\\dfrac{F_{2n+2}-1}{F_{2n+2}+1}.$",
          "Estimate the tail with Binet's formula $F_m=\\dfrac{\\varphi^{m}-\\psi^{m}}{\\sqrt5}$, where $\\varphi=\\frac{1+\\sqrt5}{2}>1$ and $\\psi=\\frac{1-\\sqrt5}{2}\\in(-1,0)$. Then $F_{2n+2}\\sim\\dfrac{\\varphi^{2n+2}}{\\sqrt5}\\to\\infty$, so $\\tan S_n=\\dfrac{F_{2n+2}-1}{F_{2n+2}+1}\\to1$. Because $\\tan^{-1}$ is continuous and $S_n\\in(0,\\tfrac{\\pi}{4})$ stays in a single branch, $S_n=\\tan^{-1}\\dfrac{F_{2n+2}-1}{F_{2n+2}+1}\\to\\tan^{-1}1.$",
          "Therefore $S=\\lim_{n\\to\\infty}S_n=\\tan^{-1}1=\\boxed{\\dfrac{\\pi}{4}}.$ The convergence is geometric at rate $\\varphi^{-2}=\\frac{3-\\sqrt5}{2}\\approx0.382$ per term, confirming the series sums rapidly to $\\frac{\\pi}{4}$ — and the limit is pinned by the $F_2=1$ anchor, the even-parity pairing being the only one whose terms are the given $\\tan^{-1}\\frac1{F_{2k+1}}$."
