    "remark": "This is the classical Fibonacci arctangent telescope (a d'Ocagne / Lucas–Cassini gem), engineered so that the dangerous step is invisible: BOTH the even pairing $\\tan^{-1}\\frac1{F_{2k}}-\\tan^{-1}\\frac1{F_{2k+2}}$ and the seemingly symmetric odd pairing $\\tan^{-1}\\frac1{F_{2k-1}}-\\tan^{-1}\\frac1{F_{2k+1}}$ telescope cleanly and both run to the anchor $\\tan^{-1}1=\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}$. The decisive difference is the parity hidden in Cassini's $(-1)^{n}$: only the even pairing puts the ODD middle index $2k+1$ inside Cassini, turning $F_{2k}F_{2k+2}+1$ into the perfect square $F_{2k+1}^{2}$ and reproducing THIS series' terms. Pair the wrong parity and the $+1$ Cassini value gives $F_{2k}^{2}+2$, a perfect telescope of the wrong series. The lesson for a top-rank student: a telescope is only valid if its TERMS match — matching the limit is necessary but never sufficient, and with Fibonacci the term-match is gated entirely by the sign $(-1)^{n}$."
