    "trap": "The fatal move is to write $\\tan^{-1}\\frac{g(k+1)-g(k)}{1+g(k)g(k+1)}=\\tan^{-1}g(k+1)-\\tan^{-1}g(k)$ for EVERY $k$ and telescope, getting $\\sum_{k=1}^{N}=\\tan^{-1}g(N+1)-\\tan^{-1}g(1)\\to\\frac{\\pi}{2}-\\tan^{-1}(-4)=\\frac{\\pi}{2}+\\tan^{-1}4$. That identity is only valid when $\\tan^{-1}g(k+1)-\\tan^{-1}g(k)\\in(-\\frac{\\pi}{2},\\frac{\\pi}{2})$, i.e. when $1+g(k)g(k+1)>0$. With $g(k)=3k-7$ the product $g(k)g(k+1)$ is positive for $k=1$ and for all $k\\ge3$, but at $k=2$ we have $g(2)=-1,\\,g(3)=2$, so $1+g(2)g(3)=-1<0$: here $g$ crosses zero and the genuine difference $\\tan^{-1}2-\\tan^{-1}(-1)=\\tan^{-1}2+\\frac{\\pi}{4}\\approx1.8925$ exceeds $\\frac{\\pi}{2}$, while the principal summand is $\\tan^{-1}(-3)\\approx-1.2490$. They differ by EXACTLY $\\pi$. So the summand is $\\big(\\tan^{-1}g(k+1)-\\tan^{-1}g(k)\\big)-\\pi$ at $k=2$ only, and the honest sum is $\\pi$ SMALLER than the naive telescope. A student who never checks the sign of $1+g(k)g(k+1)$ boxes $\\frac{\\pi}{2}+\\tan^{-1}4$ instead of $\\tan^{-1}4-\\frac{\\pi}{2}$ — wrong by a full half-turn, even though every other term telescopes flawlessly.",
    "solutions": [
      {
        "name": "Telescope with the isolated branch correction",
        "steps": [
          "Seek $g(k)=ak+b$ with $g(k+1)-g(k)=a$ constant in the numerator: matching $a=3$ and the denominator $1+g(k)g(k+1)=9k^{2}-33k+29$ forces $g(k)=3k-7$ (so $g(k)g(k+1)=(3k-7)(3k-4)=9k^{2}-33k+28$ and $1+\\text{that}=9k^{2}-33k+29$, exactly). Thus each summand equals $\\tan^{-1}\\dfrac{g(k+1)-g(k)}{1+g(k)g(k+1)}$ with $g(k)=3k-7$.",
          "The subtraction identity $\\tan^{-1}\\frac{u-v}{1+uv}=\\tan^{-1}u-\\tan^{-1}v$ holds only when $1+uv>0$. Here $1+g(k)g(k+1)=9k^{2}-33k+29>0$ for $k=1$ and all $k\\ge3$, but equals $-1<0$ at $k=2$, where $g(2)=-1<0<2=g(3)$. So for $k\\ne2$ the summand is cleanly $\\tan^{-1}g(k+1)-\\tan^{-1}g(k)$; at $k=2$, since the true difference $\\tan^{-1}2-\\tan^{-1}(-1)\\in(\\frac{\\pi}{2},\\pi)$ overshoots the principal range by $\\pi$, the principal summand is $\\tan^{-1}(-3)=\\big(\\tan^{-1}2-\\tan^{-1}(-1)\\big)-\\pi$. Hence $\\tan^{-1}\\frac{3}{9k^{2}-33k+29}=\\big(\\tan^{-1}g(k+1)-\\tan^{-1}g(k)\\big)-\\pi\\,[\\,k=2\\,].$",
          "Sum to $N\\ge2$: the bracketed part telescopes to $\\tan^{-1}g(N+1)-\\tan^{-1}g(1)=\\tan^{-1}(3N-4)-\\tan^{-1}(-4)$, and the lone correction contributes $-\\pi$. So $S_N=\\tan^{-1}(3N-4)+\\tan^{-1}4-\\pi$. Let $N\\to\\infty$: $\\tan^{-1}(3N-4)\\to\\frac{\\pi}{2}$, giving $S=\\frac{\\pi}{2}+\\tan^{-1}4-\\pi=\\boxed{\\tan^{-1}4-\\dfrac{\\pi}{2}}$ (equivalently $-\\tan^{-1}\\frac14$)."
        ]
      },
      {
        "name": "Complex Gaussian arguments with winding count",
        "steps": [
          "Write each summand as an argument: for $g(k)=3k-7$, $\\arg\\dfrac{1+i\\,g(k+1)}{1+i\\,g(k)}=\\tan^{-1}g(k+1)-\\tan^{-1}g(k)\\pmod{2\\pi}$, while the principal $\\tan^{-1}\\frac{3}{1+g(k)g(k+1)}$ is the value of that argument in $(-\\frac{\\pi}{2},\\frac{\\pi}{2})$. The two agree exactly when the quotient $\\frac{1+ig(k+1)}{1+ig(k)}$ has positive real part, i.e. $\\mathrm{Re}=\\frac{1+g(k)g(k+1)}{1+g(k)^2}>0$ — failing only at $k=2$, where the quotient lands in the left half-plane and the principal arctan is short by $\\pi$.",
          "Telescope the product $\\prod_{k=1}^{N}\\frac{1+i\\,g(k+1)}{1+i\\,g(k)}=\\frac{1+i\\,g(N+1)}{1+i\\,g(1)}=\\frac{1+i(3N-4)}{1-4i}$. Its principal argument is $\\arg(1+i(3N-4))-\\arg(1-4i)\\to\\frac{\\pi}{2}-(-\\tan^{-1}4)=\\frac{\\pi}{2}+\\tan^{-1}4$ as $N\\to\\infty$. This equals $\\sum_{k=1}^{N}\\big(\\tan^{-1}g(k+1)-\\tan^{-1}g(k)\\big)$, the UNCORRECTED total.",
          "The realized sum of principal summands differs from this product-argument by $-\\pi$ for each $k$ whose factor crossed into the left half-plane, here only $k=2$. Therefore $S=\\big(\\frac{\\pi}{2}+\\tan^{-1}4\\big)-\\pi=\\boxed{\\tan^{-1}4-\\dfrac{\\pi}{2}}.$"
        ]
      },
      {
        "name": "Split off the rogue term, telescope the clean tail",
        "steps": [
          "Isolate $k=2$: $S=\\tan^{-1}(-3)+\\Big(\\tan^{-1}\\tfrac{3}{5}+\\sum_{k\\ge3}\\tan^{-1}\\tfrac{3}{9k^{2}-33k+29}\\Big)$. For every $k$ in the retained block $1+g(k)g(k+1)>0$, so those terms obey the clean identity $\\tan^{-1}g(k+1)-\\tan^{-1}g(k)$ with no correction.",
          "Telescope the clean block from $k=1$ skipping $k=2$: $\\big(\\tan^{-1}g(2)-\\tan^{-1}g(1)\\big)+\\sum_{k\\ge3}\\big(\\tan^{-1}g(k+1)-\\tan^{-1}g(k)\\big)=\\big(\\tan^{-1}(-1)-\\tan^{-1}(-4)\\big)+\\big(\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}-\\tan^{-1}2\\big)$, since the second telescope runs $\\tan^{-1}g(k+1)$ from $g(3)=2$ up to $\\lim g(k+1)=+\\infty$.",
          "Add the rogue term $\\tan^{-1}(-3)$: $S=\\tan^{-1}(-3)+\\big(-\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}+\\tan^{-1}4\\big)+\\big(\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}-\\tan^{-1}2\\big)$. Using $\\tan^{-1}3-\\tan^{-1}2=\\tan^{-1}\\frac{1}{7}$ would re-tangle things; instead note $-\\tan^{-1}3-\\tan^{-1}2+\\tan^{-1}4+\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}=\\tan^{-1}4-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$ numerically (both $\\approx-0.24498$), confirming $S=\\boxed{\\tan^{-1}4-\\dfrac{\\pi}{2}}$. The arithmetic exposes the same $-\\pi$ deficit packaged into the single skipped term."
        ]
      }
    ],
    "remark": "This is the only 'true branch-in-a-telescope' specimen: a sum that telescopes perfectly except at ONE index where the linear interior $g(k)=3k-7$ changes sign, sending $1+g(k)g(k+1)$ negative and forcing the subtraction formula to absorb a $+\\pi$. The honest value $\\tan^{-1}4-\\frac{\\pi}{2}=-\\tan^{-1}\\frac14$ is NEGATIVE, a tell-tale that a naive telescope (which would yield the positive $\\frac{\\pi}{2}+\\tan^{-1}4$) has skipped a half-turn. The general principle for top-rank students: before collapsing $\\sum\\tan^{-1}\\frac{a_{k+1}-a_k}{1+a_ka_{k+1}}$, check the sign of every denominator $1+a_ka_{k+1}$ — each negative one costs exactly $\\pm\\pi$, and a single sign change anywhere in the interior sequence poisons the whole closed form."
