          "Pin each by one clean sample. At $x=1^{-}$: $\\cot^{-1}\\dfrac{1-x^2}{2x}\\to\\cot^{-1}0=\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$, $\\tan^{-1}x\\to\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}$, $\\tan^{-1}\\frac{1-x}{1+x}\\to\\tan^{-1}0=0$, giving $F\\to\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}-\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}+0=\\boxed{\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}}$ on $(0,1)$. At $x=-1^{+}$: $\\cot^{-1}\\dfrac{1-x^2}{2x}\\to\\cot^{-1}0^{-}=\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$, $\\tan^{-1}x\\to-\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}$, $\\tan^{-1}\\frac{1-x}{1+x}\\to+\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$ (as $\\frac{1-x}{1+x}\\to+\\infty$), giving $F\\to\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}+\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}+\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}=\\boxed{\\tfrac{5\\pi}{4}}$ on $(-1,0)$. The derivative is zero on both pieces, yet the boundary samples expose the half-turn gap between them."
