    "remark": "The whole problem turns on the principal range of $\\cot^{-1}$, which is $(0,\\pi)$ with no negative output — so $\\cot^{-1}(\\cot 2t)=2t$ only while $2t\\in(0,\\pi)$, and silently becomes $2t+\\pi$ the instant $x$ goes negative and $2t$ drops below $0$. The Machin pair $\\tan^{-1}x+\\tan^{-1}\\frac{1-x}{1+x}=\\frac{\\pi}{4}$ is a true constant across $x=0$ and is there only as a decoy: it lulls the student into expecting one global constant. The lesson for top-rank students is that 'collapse to a constant' is a statement about a DOMAIN, never a formula; a $\\cot^{-1}$, $\\cos^{-1}$ or $\\sec^{-1}$ whose argument changes sign will inject an exact $\\pm\\pi$ that the derivative cannot see (a constant offset differentiates to $0$), so the only safe proof either substitutes and tracks which interval the angle lands in, or differentiates AND re-pins the constant separately on each connected piece of the domain."
