    "remark": "The whole problem is a single trigonometric rotation in disguise: $\\tfrac12\\cos\\theta+\\tfrac{\\sqrt3}{2}\\sin\\theta=\\cos(\\theta-\\tfrac{\\pi}{3})$ rotates the angle by $60^\\circ$, and the second arccosine tries to undo it. It succeeds only while the rotated angle $\\theta-\\tfrac{\\pi}{3}$ stays in $[-\\pi,0]$ — i.e. for $\\theta\\le\\tfrac{\\pi}{3}$, the slice $x\\in[\\tfrac12,1]$ where $F\\equiv\\tfrac{\\pi}{3}$. Push $\\theta$ past $\\tfrac{\\pi}{3}$ and the principal branch of $\\cos^{-1}$ reflects $\\theta-\\tfrac{\\pi}{3}$ to $+(\\theta-\\tfrac{\\pi}{3})$ instead of cancelling it, so $F$ stops being constant and climbs as $2\\cos^{-1}x-\\tfrac{\\pi}{3}$, overshooting by a full $\\tfrac{2\\pi}{3}$ at $x=-\\tfrac12$. The top-rank lesson: $\\cos^{-1}(\\cos\\phi)=\\phi$ is a half-truth — it is $|\\phi|$ on $[-\\pi,\\pi]$ — and any collapse identity built on it lives only on the sub-interval where the reflected angle keeps its sign. Part (b) is the payoff: a solver who swallowed the false constant declares 'no solution', while the one who found the second branch lands the clean root $\\cos\\tfrac{5\\pi}{12}=\\tfrac{\\sqrt6-\\sqrt2}{4}$."
