    "statement": "Let $\\Phi(x)=\\tan^{-1}x+\\tan^{-1}\\!\\dfrac{1}{x}$ on $x\\ne0$, using the principal branch $\\tan^{-1}t\\in\\left(-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2},\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}\\right)$. (a) Prove that $\\Phi$ collapses to a constant on each side of the origin: $\\Phi(x)=+\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$ for $x>0$ and $\\Phi(x)=-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$ for $x<0$, even though $\\Phi'(x)=0$ wherever it is defined. (b) A student is then asked to evaluate \\[ I=\\int_{-1}^{1} e^{\\,\\tan^{-1}x+\\tan^{-1}(1/x)}\\,\\frac{dx}{1+x^{2}}. \\] He notes $\\tfrac{dx}{1+x^{2}}=d(\\tan^{-1}x)$, declares the exponent equal to $\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$ by part (a), pulls out $e^{\\pi/2}$, and reports $I=\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}e^{\\pi/2}$. Decide whether he is right, and give the exact value of $I$.",
