    "trap": "The exponent $\\Phi(x)$ is $+\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$ only on $x>0$; on the LEFT half of the symmetric interval $[-1,1]$ it is $-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$. The fatal move is to treat the well-known collapse $\\tan^{-1}x+\\tan^{-1}\\frac1x=\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$ as a single global constant and factor $e^{\\pi/2}$ out across the WHOLE interval, as if the $x=0$ fold were a removable point. It is not removable: $\\Phi$ jumps by $\\pi$ there. Honestly splitting at $0$ gives $e^{\\pi/2}\\!\\int_0^1\\frac{dx}{1+x^2}+e^{-\\pi/2}\\!\\int_{-1}^0\\frac{dx}{1+x^2}=\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}(e^{\\pi/2}+e^{-\\pi/2})=\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}\\cosh\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$. The naive answer $\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}e^{\\pi/2}$ overshoots by exactly $\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}\\sinh\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$ — the entire contribution of the negative branch, silently overwritten. Note $\\Phi'\\equiv0$ is a TRUE statement that lures the student: a derivative that vanishes everywhere it exists need not mean the function is one constant across a gap in its domain.",
