          "Rewrite the exponent in $u$. With $x=\\tan u$: for $u\\in(0,\\tfrac{\\pi}{4})$ (i.e. $x>0$), $\\tan^{-1}\\tfrac1x=\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}-u$ so $\\Phi=u+(\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}-u)=\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$; for $u\\in(-\\tfrac{\\pi}{4},0)$ (i.e. $x<0$), $\\tan^{-1}\\tfrac1x=-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}-u$ so $\\Phi=-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$. The integral becomes $I=\\displaystyle\\int_{-\\pi/4}^{0}e^{-\\pi/2}\\,du+\\int_{0}^{\\pi/4}e^{\\pi/2}\\,du$ — the substitution turns the curved integrand into two flat boxes, but the fold at $u=0$ survives and still forbids a single antiderivative.",
