    "remark": "The seductive fact is the TRUE statement $\\Phi'\\equiv0$: a vanishing derivative usually means “constant.” But $\\Phi$'s domain has a hole at $x=0$, and across that hole $\\Phi$ jumps from $-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$ to $+\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$ — the collapse $\\tan^{-1}x+\\tan^{-1}\\frac1x$ produces TWO constants, not one. Any computation that integrates, exponentiates, or otherwise transports a value across the fold while pretending it is a single constant silently deletes the entire negative branch. The even–odd view is the cleanest diagnostic: the honest integrand carries an odd $\\operatorname{sgn}(x)\\sinh\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$ piece that integrates to zero, whereas the naive “$\\Phi\\equiv\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$” turns it into a nonzero even bump. Top-rank lesson: before factoring a “constant” out of an integral, confirm it is constant on the WHOLE interval of integration, fold and all."
