    "remark": "Two independent traps are stacked here. First, $\\frac{a-b}{1+ab}=1$ identically tempts one to declare a single global constant $\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}$, but the difference formula only holds when $1+ab>0$; here $1+ab=\\frac{x^{2}+1}{x+1}$ flips sign at the pole $x=-1$, injecting a $-\\pi$ on the far side so the collapse produces TWO constants ($\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}$ and $-\\tfrac{3\\pi}{4}$). Second, and more subtly, even a student who finds both constants may leap from \"the value jumps\" to \"the slope jumps.\" It does not: the step part is locally constant, so it contributes nothing to $F'$, and the only surviving derivative $\\frac{2x}{1+x^{4}}$ sails continuously through $x=-1$ with the common one-sided value $-1$. The graph is a cliff with no kink — a pure zeroth-order (value) discontinuity carrying a continuous first-order (slope) behaviour. Top-rank lesson: classify a singularity ORDER by order. A jump in $F$ and a jump in $F'$ are logically independent events; a collapsing inverse-trig identity hides its branch jump inside a locally-constant term that the derivative literally cannot detect, so the smoothness question must be answered by computing $F'$ on each side, never inferred from the value jump."
