    "statement": "Using principal branches $\\sin^{-1}t\\in\\left[-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2},\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}\\right]$ and $\\cos^{-1}t\\in[0,\\pi]$, find every real $x$ satisfying \\[ \\sin^{-1}x+\\sin^{-1}(2x)\\;=\\;\\cos^{-1}x+\\cos^{-1}(2x), \\] and state how many solutions there are. A student rearranges with $\\sin^{-1}t+\\cos^{-1}t=\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$, reaches a clean polynomial, and triumphantly reports both of its roots. Verify the count honestly: the polynomial's degree is NOT the number of solutions.",
    "answer": "\\[\\boxed{\\,x=\\dfrac{1}{\\sqrt5}\\ \\text{(exactly one solution)}\\,}\\]",
    "trap": "Squaring sends BOTH region information and sign information to the floor. The honest reduction collapses the equation to $\\sin^{-1}x+\\sin^{-1}(2x)=\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$, whose domain is $|x|\\le\\tfrac12$. Writing $\\sin^{-1}(2x)=\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}-\\sin^{-1}x=\\cos^{-1}x$ and taking sines gives $2x=\\sqrt{1-x^{2}}$, then $5x^{2}=1$, so the candidates are $x=\\pm\\tfrac{1}{\\sqrt5}$. The lethal subtlety is that $\\tfrac{1}{\\sqrt5}\\approx0.447<\\tfrac12$, so $x=-\\tfrac{1}{\\sqrt5}$ ALSO lies inside the domain $|x|\\le\\tfrac12$ — a naive domain check does NOT reject it. It is extraneous for a deeper reason: the constant the left side collapses to is region-dependent. For $x>0$ both $\\sin^{-1}$ terms are positive and the sum can reach $+\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$; for $x<0$ both are negative and the sum equals $-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$, never $+\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$. Equivalently $\\sin^{-1}(2x)=\\cos^{-1}x$ forces the left side into $[-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2},\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}]$ to meet the right side's $[0,\\pi]$, which is possible only where BOTH lie in $[0,\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}]$, i.e. $x\\ge0$. Squaring $2x=\\sqrt{1-x^{2}}$ silently admitted the sign-flipped root $2x=-\\sqrt{1-x^{2}}$, which is the equation $\\sin^{-1}x+\\sin^{-1}(2x)=-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$ in disguise. So the polynomial has two roots but the equation has exactly one.",
