          "Resolve each block on $[-1,1]$. With $x=\\tan\\theta$, $\\theta=\\tan^{-1}x\\in[-\\tfrac{\\pi}{4},\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}]$, we have $\\frac{2x}{1+x^{2}}=\\sin 2\\theta$ with $2\\theta\\in[-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2},\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}]$, so $\\sin^{-1}\\frac{2x}{1+x^{2}}=2\\theta=2\\tan^{-1}x$ for ALL $x\\in[-1,1]$. But $\\frac{1-x^{2}}{1+x^{2}}=\\cos 2\\theta$ with $2\\theta\\in[-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2},\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}]$, and $\\cos^{-1}(\\cos 2\\theta)=\\lvert 2\\theta\\rvert$, so $\\cos^{-1}\\frac{1-x^{2}}{1+x^{2}}=2\\tan^{-1}x$ for $x\\ge0$ but $=-2\\tan^{-1}x$ for $x<0$. Finally $\\cot^{-1}x=\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}-\\tan^{-1}x$ everywhere.",
          "Add. For $x\\in[0,1]$: $f=2\\tan^{-1}x+2\\tan^{-1}x+(\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}-\\tan^{-1}x)=3\\tan^{-1}x+\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$. For $x\\in[-1,0]$: $f=2\\tan^{-1}x-2\\tan^{-1}x+(\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}-\\tan^{-1}x)=\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}-\\tan^{-1}x$. The pieces agree at $x=0$ (both give $\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$), so $f$ is continuous with a corner there; the student's single formula is correct only on $[0,1]$.",
          "Sweep each monotone piece. On $[-1,0]$, $\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}-\\tan^{-1}x$ is decreasing from $\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}-(-\\tfrac{\\pi}{4})=\\tfrac{3\\pi}{4}$ down to $\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$. On $[0,1]$, $3\\tan^{-1}x+\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$ is increasing from $\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$ up to $3\\cdot\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}+\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}=\\tfrac{5\\pi}{4}$. The two images $[\\tfrac{\\pi}{2},\\tfrac{3\\pi}{4}]\\cup[\\tfrac{\\pi}{2},\\tfrac{5\\pi}{4}]$ union to $\\boxed{[\\tfrac{\\pi}{2},\\tfrac{5\\pi}{4}]}$, with minimum $\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$ at $x=0$ and maximum $\\tfrac{5\\pi}{4}$ at $x=1$."
