          "At $x=0$ the one-sided slopes are $f'(0^{-})=-1$ and $f'(0^{+})=+3$: a genuine corner (non-differentiable), so the naive smooth formula $3\\tan^{-1}x+\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$ — whose slope is the single value $3/(1+x^2)$ — cannot describe $f$ near $0$. The minimum value is $f(0)=\\sin^{-1}0+\\cos^{-1}1+\\cot^{-1}0=0+0+\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}=\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$.",
          "Since the only critical behaviour is the corner-minimum, the maximum is at an endpoint: $f(-1)=\\sin^{-1}(-1)+\\cos^{-1}0+\\cot^{-1}(-1)=-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}+\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}+\\tfrac{3\\pi}{4}=\\tfrac{3\\pi}{4}$ and $f(1)=\\sin^{-1}1+\\cos^{-1}0+\\cot^{-1}1=\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}+\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}+\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}=\\tfrac{5\\pi}{4}$. The larger is $\\tfrac{5\\pi}{4}$. By continuity $f$ attains every value between $\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$ and $\\tfrac{5\\pi}{4}$, so the range is $\\boxed{[\\tfrac{\\pi}{2},\\tfrac{5\\pi}{4}]}$."
