    "remark": "Two double-angle collapses look like twins but are not: $\\sin^{-1}\\frac{2x}{1+x^{2}}=2\\tan^{-1}x$ holds across all of $[-1,1]$, while $\\cos^{-1}\\frac{1-x^{2}}{1+x^{2}}=2\\lvert\\tan^{-1}x\\rvert$ folds at $x=0$ because $\\cos^{-1}$ refuses negative output. Applying the same formula to both is the mismatched-domain fallacy. The fold turns what the student reads as one smooth increasing curve into a V with an asymmetric corner ($-1$ on the left, $+3$ on the right), placing the global minimum $\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$ exactly where the naive reduction predicts an ordinary interior value. Top-rank lesson: each inverse-trig collapse identity carries its OWN domain of validity, and a sum of collapses inherits the corners of every factor — sign-check each block before pretending the whole expression is a single formula."
