    "statement": "Let $a$ be a real parameter. Using the principal branch $\\sin^{-1}t\\in\\left[-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2},\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}\\right]$, consider the equation in the real unknown $x$ \\[ \\sin^{-1}x \\;+\\; \\sin^{-1}(a-x) \\;=\\; \\frac{\\pi}{2}. \\] Determine the complete set of values of $a$ for which this equation has exactly two real solutions $x$, and justify both the interval and the inclusion or exclusion of each endpoint. A quick worker moves $\\sin^{-1}x$ across, takes sine of $\\sin^{-1}(a-x)=\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}-\\sin^{-1}x$, gets $a-x=\\sqrt{1-x^{2}}$, squares to the quadratic $2x^{2}-2ax+(a^{2}-1)=0$, and concludes \"two roots whenever the discriminant is positive and both lie in $[-1,1]$,\" reporting the symmetric window $a\\in(-\\sqrt2,\\sqrt2)$. That answer is wrong on both ends and across half its length. Find the honest window.",
