          "Rationality of part (a): $g(k)\\in\\mathbb{Q}_{\\ge0}$ iff $\\dfrac{1-k}{1+k}=t^{2}$ for some rational $t\\ge0$. Solving for $k$: $t^{2}(1+k)=1-k\\Rightarrow k(1+t^{2})=1-t^{2}\\Rightarrow k=\\dfrac{1-t^{2}}{1+t^{2}}$. As $t$ runs over $\\mathbb{Q}_{\\ge0}$ this $k$ runs over rationals in $(-1,1]$ of Pythagorean type (e.g. $t=\\tfrac13\\!\\to k=\\tfrac45$, $t=3\\!\\to k=-\\tfrac45$); it is NOT all of $\\mathbb{Q}\\cap(-1,1]$, since $k=\\tfrac12$ forces $t^{2}=\\tfrac13$, impossible. Hence $\\boxed{g(k)\\in\\mathbb{Q}\\iff k=\\dfrac{1-t^{2}}{1+t^{2}},\\ t\\in\\mathbb{Q}_{\\ge0}}$.",
