    "remark": "The whole investigation is governed by one structural fact the right-triangle picture would have hidden: the half-angle $\\tfrac12\\arccos k$ is trapped in $\\left[0,\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}\\right)$, so $\\tan$ of it is forced non-negative — the surd's $\\pm$ is a fiction, and $g$ can never be a negative rational. Rationality then becomes a genuine Diophantine condition: $\\tfrac{1-k}{1+k}$ must be a rational square, which is exactly the Weierstrass / Pythagorean-triple parametrisation $k=\\tfrac{1-t^{2}}{1+t^{2}}$ that converts angles into rational points on the unit circle. Far from \"every rational $k$\", only the cosines of Pythagorean angles qualify ($k=\\tfrac45,\\tfrac35,\\tfrac{7}{25},\\dots$ and their negatives), while pedestrian rationals like $k=\\tfrac12$ give irrational $g$. Finally the sign content is subtle precisely because $g\\ge0$ everywhere: the information about $\\operatorname{sgn}k$ lives not in the sign of $g$ but in whether the value crosses the watershed $g=1$ (half-angle $=\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}$), and the reciprocal involution $g(-k)=1/g(k)$ makes that crossing exact. Top-rank lesson: when a half-angle inverse-trig value looks like it could be either sign, first locate the half-angle's mandatory interval — it usually removes the ambiguity and turns a surd question into a clean number-theoretic one."
