    "statement": "Using the principal branches $\\arcsin t\\in\\left[-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2},\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}\\right]$ and $\\arccos t\\in[0,\\pi]$, let \\[ \\theta \\;=\\; \\arcsin\\!\\left(-\\tfrac{3}{5}\\right)\\;-\\;\\arccos\\!\\left(-\\tfrac{5}{13}\\right). \\] Evaluate $\\cos\\theta$ exactly. Before reaching for a single-inverse closed form, settle one thing first: prove which side of $-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$ the angle $\\theta$ falls on. A classmate finds $\\tan\\theta=\\tfrac{33}{56}$ and immediately writes $\\theta=\\arctan\\tfrac{33}{56}$, then reports $\\cos\\theta=\\tfrac{56}{65}$. Decide whether that is right, and give the correct value with proof of the quadrant.",
    "answer": "\\[\\boxed{-\\dfrac{56}{65}}\\]",
    "trap": "Both arctangent and arcsine quietly return values in $\\left(-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2},\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}\\right)$, so any move that re-expresses $\\theta$ as $\\arctan(\\text{something})$ or $\\arcsin(\\text{something})$ silently forces $\\theta$ into that window. But the true $\\theta$ is NOT there. Watch the sizes: $\\arcsin\\!\\left(-\\tfrac35\\right)\\approx -36.87^{\\circ}$ is a small negative angle, while $\\arccos\\!\\left(-\\tfrac{5}{13}\\right)\\approx 112.62^{\\circ}$ is OBTUSE (its cosine is negative, so it exceeds $\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$). Subtracting a large obtuse angle from a small negative one drives the difference down to $\\theta\\approx -149.49^{\\circ}$, i.e. $\\theta\\in\\left(-\\pi,-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}\\right)$ — it has overshot $-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$ into the third quadrant (measured from $0$, the terminal side sits in QIII). There $\\cos\\theta<0$. The classmate's $\\tan\\theta=\\tfrac{33}{56}$ is genuinely correct, but $\\tan$ has period $\\pi$, so $\\tan\\theta=\\tfrac{33}{56}$ is satisfied by BOTH $\\arctan\\tfrac{33}{56}\\approx 30.51^{\\circ}$ (QI) and $\\arctan\\tfrac{33}{56}-\\pi\\approx -149.49^{\\circ}$ (QIII); only the second is $\\theta$. Reading $\\cos$ off the QI representative gives $+\\tfrac{56}{65}$; the QIII reality gives $-\\tfrac{56}{65}$. Identically, the seduction $\\sin\\theta=-\\tfrac{33}{65}\\Rightarrow\\theta=\\arcsin\\!\\left(-\\tfrac{33}{65}\\right)$ fails for the same reason: $\\sin$ alone cannot separate the two angles whose sines agree, and the cosine is exactly what they disagree on. The whole problem is that $\\cos\\theta$ is undetermined by $\\tan\\theta$ (or by $\\sin\\theta$) until the quadrant is earned by an inequality.",
