          "Apply $\\cos(a-b)=\\cos a\\cos b+\\sin a\\sin b$. This identity is valid for ALL real $a,b$, so it sidesteps the quadrant question entirely: $\\cos\\theta=\\tfrac45\\cdot\\left(-\\tfrac{5}{13}\\right)+\\left(-\\tfrac35\\right)\\cdot\\tfrac{12}{13}=-\\tfrac{20}{65}-\\tfrac{36}{65}=-\\tfrac{56}{65}.$",
          "The minus sign emerges automatically from $\\cos b=-\\tfrac{5}{13}<0$ — the obtuseness of $b$ is baked into its cosine. Therefore $\\cos\\theta=\\boxed{-\\dfrac{56}{65}}$, and the classmate's $+\\tfrac{56}{65}$ is wrong by a sign."
