    "remark": "The engine here is that $\\cos\\theta$ is invisible to $\\tan\\theta$ and to $\\sin\\theta$: both $\\theta$ and a partner angle (differing by $\\pi$, or reflected through $-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$) share the same tangent and the same sine, and they disagree precisely in cosine. So any collapse of $\\theta$ into a single $\\arctan$ or $\\arcsin$ — whose outputs are imprisoned in $\\left(-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2},\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}\\right)$ — quietly picks the WRONG one of the pair the instant the true angle has overshot $-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$. The tell that it must overshoot is the obtuse $\\arccos\\!\\left(-\\tfrac{5}{13}\\right)$: subtracting an angle bigger than $\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$ from a small negative angle cannot stay inside $\\left[-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2},\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}\\right]$. Two cures are worth internalizing. The robust one is to never collapse at all: the sum-to-product expansion $\\cos(a-b)=\\cos a\\cos b+\\sin a\\sin b$ holds for every real pair and lets the negative $\\cos b$ deliver the minus sign by itself. The elegant one is to read $\\theta$ as an argument of a complex product; the rectangular signs $(\\operatorname{Re}<0,\\ \\operatorname{Im}<0)$ announce QIII at a glance. Top-rank discipline: $\\tan\\theta=k$ never determines $\\cos\\theta$ — earn the quadrant first, then choose the sign of the square root."
