    "statement": "Throughout, $\\arccos t\\in[0,\\pi]$ is the principal branch. For $x\\in[-1,1]$ write $\\theta=\\arccos x$, so $\\cos\\theta=x$. The cosine doubling map sends $x$ to $\\cos(2\\theta)=2x^{2}-1$, and the angle $\\theta$ to its double $2\\theta$. Call $x$ a self-reproducing point when it satisfies BOTH of the following: \\[ \\text{(i)}\\quad \\cos\\!\\big(2\\arccos x\\big)=x, \\qquad\\qquad \\text{(ii)}\\quad \\arccos\\!\\big(2x^{2}-1\\big)=2\\arccos x. \\] Condition (i) says $x$ is a fixed point of the doubling map (the doubled angle reproduces the original $x$ as its cosine); condition (ii) says the doubled angle $2\\arccos x$ is itself a legitimate principal arccosine value, so that reading the doubled cosine back through $\\arccos$ returns exactly $2\\theta$. Determine all self-reproducing $x\\in[-1,1]$. A student writes: \"From (i), $2x^{2}-1=x$, so $2x^{2}-x-1=0$, giving $x=1$ or $x=-\\tfrac12$. And (ii) is just the cosine double-angle identity $\\cos 2\\theta=2\\cos^{2}\\theta-1$ read backwards, which is always true, so it adds nothing. Hence both $x=1$ and $x=-\\tfrac12$ are self-reproducing.\" Exactly one of these two roots is genuine. Find it, and explain precisely why the other is extraneous.",
    "answer": "\\[\\boxed{x=1}\\]",
    "trap": "The student treats (ii) as the universal identity $\\cos 2\\theta=2\\cos^{2}\\theta-1$ run backwards and declares it automatic. It is NOT. The genuine universal identity is $\\cos\\!\\big(2\\arccos x\\big)=2x^{2}-1$ — that is condition (i)-flavoured and holds for every $x$. But condition (ii), $\\arccos(2x^{2}-1)=2\\arccos x$, is a statement about ANGLES, and $\\arccos$ can only return a value in $[0,\\pi]$. Taking $\\arccos$ of both sides of $\\cos(2\\theta)=2x^{2}-1$ gives $\\arccos(2x^{2}-1)=\\arccos(\\cos 2\\theta)$, and $\\arccos(\\cos 2\\theta)=2\\theta$ ONLY when $2\\theta\\le\\pi$, i.e. $\\theta\\le\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$, i.e. $x\\ge0$. For $x=1$ we have $\\theta=0$ and $2\\theta=0\\le\\pi$, so (ii) holds. For $x=-\\tfrac12$ we have $\\theta=\\tfrac{2\\pi}{3}$ and $2\\theta=\\tfrac{4\\pi}{3}>\\pi$: the doubled angle has overshot a straight angle, so it is no longer a principal arccosine value. Indeed $\\arccos\\!\\big(2(-\\tfrac12)^{2}-1\\big)=\\arccos(-\\tfrac12)=\\tfrac{2\\pi}{3}$, whereas $2\\arccos(-\\tfrac12)=\\tfrac{4\\pi}{3}$, and $\\tfrac{2\\pi}{3}\\ne\\tfrac{4\\pi}{3}$. So $x=-\\tfrac12$ satisfies the quadratic (i) but fails the angle equation (ii); it is extraneous. The fixed-point algebra is colour-blind to the hidden $[0,\\pi]$ ceiling.",
    "solutions": [
      {
        "name": "The range gate on the doubled angle",
        "steps": [
          "Condition (i): with $\\theta=\\arccos x$, the identity $\\cos(2\\theta)=2\\cos^{2}\\theta-1=2x^{2}-1$ holds for all $x$, so (i) reads $2x^{2}-1=x$, i.e. $2x^{2}-x-1=(2x+1)(x-1)=0$, giving the two candidates $x=1$ and $x=-\\tfrac12$.",
          "Condition (ii) is the gate. Apply $\\arccos$ to $\\cos(2\\theta)=2x^{2}-1$: the right side becomes $\\arccos(2x^{2}-1)$ and the left becomes $\\arccos(\\cos 2\\theta)$. Now $\\arccos(\\cos\\alpha)=\\alpha$ holds precisely when $\\alpha\\in[0,\\pi]$; for $\\alpha\\in(\\pi,2\\pi]$ instead $\\arccos(\\cos\\alpha)=2\\pi-\\alpha$. Thus (ii) $\\Leftrightarrow 2\\theta\\le\\pi\\Leftrightarrow\\theta\\le\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}\\Leftrightarrow x\\ge0$.",
          "Test the candidates against $x\\ge0$. For $x=1$: $\\theta=0$, $2\\theta=0\\le\\pi$, so (ii) holds and $x=1$ is self-reproducing. For $x=-\\tfrac12$: $\\theta=\\tfrac{2\\pi}{3}$, $2\\theta=\\tfrac{4\\pi}{3}>\\pi$, so (ii) fails — $\\arccos(-\\tfrac12)=\\tfrac{2\\pi}{3}\\ne\\tfrac{4\\pi}{3}=2\\arccos(-\\tfrac12)$. Hence the unique self-reproducing value is $\\boxed{x=1}$."
        ]
      },
      {
        "name": "Parametrise by the angle and use injectivity of cosine on $[0,\\pi]$",
        "steps": [
          "Put $x=\\cos\\theta$ with $\\theta\\in[0,\\pi]$ (a bijection onto $[-1,1]$). Condition (i) becomes $\\cos 2\\theta=\\cos\\theta$. Condition (ii) becomes $\\arccos(\\cos 2\\theta)=2\\theta$, which by definition of $\\arccos$ requires $2\\theta\\in[0,\\pi]$, i.e. $\\theta\\in[0,\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}]$.",
          "On the admissible window $\\theta\\in[0,\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}]$ we automatically have both $\\theta$ and $2\\theta$ inside $[0,\\pi]$, where $\\cos$ is strictly decreasing, hence injective. So $\\cos 2\\theta=\\cos\\theta$ forces $2\\theta=\\theta$, i.e. $\\theta=0$, giving $x=\\cos 0=1$.",
          "Check the other branch: outside the window, $\\cos 2\\theta=\\cos\\theta$ also admits $2\\theta=2\\pi-\\theta$, i.e. $\\theta=\\tfrac{2\\pi}{3}$ (so $x=\\cos\\tfrac{2\\pi}{3}=-\\tfrac12$). But $\\theta=\\tfrac{2\\pi}{3}>\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$ makes $2\\theta=\\tfrac{4\\pi}{3}\\notin[0,\\pi]$, so condition (ii) fails there. Only $\\theta=0$ survives, and the unique answer is $\\boxed{x=1}$."
        ]
      },
      {
        "name": "Force both conditions onto one footing via $\\arccos(2x^{2}-1)$ in closed form",
        "steps": [
          "Compute $\\arccos(2x^{2}-1)$ directly. For $x\\ge0$, $2x^{2}-1=\\cos(2\\arccos x)$ with $2\\arccos x\\in[0,\\pi]$, so $\\arccos(2x^{2}-1)=2\\arccos x$. For $x<0$, $2\\arccos x\\in(\\pi,2\\pi]$, so $\\arccos(2x^{2}-1)=2\\pi-2\\arccos x$. This is the exact piecewise value, no ambiguity.",
          "Now impose (ii): $\\arccos(2x^{2}-1)=2\\arccos x$. The $x\\ge0$ branch makes (ii) an identity (it holds for every $x\\in[0,1]$), while the $x<0$ branch requires $2\\pi-2\\arccos x=2\\arccos x$, i.e. $\\arccos x=\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$, i.e. $x=0$ — which is not in $x<0$. So (ii) is equivalent to $x\\in[0,1]$.",
          "Intersect with (i)'s candidates $\\{1,-\\tfrac12\\}$: only $x=1$ lies in $[0,1]$. (One verifies $x=1$ on the nose: $\\cos(2\\arccos 1)=\\cos 0=1$ and $\\arccos(2\\cdot1-1)=\\arccos 1=0=2\\arccos 1$.) Therefore the unique self-reproducing value is $\\boxed{x=1}$."
        ]
      }
    ],
    "remark": "The deceit is that conditions (i) and (ii) look like the same double-angle identity wearing two hats, so (ii) seems free. They are not interchangeable: (i) lives on the cosine line, where $\\cos(2\\arccos x)=2x^{2}-1$ is unconditionally true, but (ii) lives on the angle circle, where reading a doubled angle back through $\\arccos$ is legal only while that angle stays under the straight-angle ceiling $\\pi$. The root $x=-\\tfrac12$ doubles its angle from $\\tfrac{2\\pi}{3}$ to $\\tfrac{4\\pi}{3}$, sailing past $\\pi$, so $\\arccos$ cannot return it and the root is amputated — a fully geometric reason, not an algebraic slip. The clean takeaway for a top-rank solver: whenever you 'cancel' an inverse function against its function ($\\arccos(\\cos\\alpha)$, $\\arcsin(\\sin\\alpha)$, $\\arctan(\\tan\\alpha)$) after a doubling, halving, or summing of angles, the cancellation is conditional on the resulting angle landing inside the inverse function's own principal range. Solve the algebra, then audit every candidate against that range; the fixed-point quadratic will happily hand you ghosts that the range gate must exorcise."
