    "statement": "Throughout, $\\arctan t\\in\\left(-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2},\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}\\right)$ is the principal branch. For real $x$ put $\\theta=\\arctan x$ and consider the doubled angle $2\\theta=2\\arctan x$. The Mobius (tangent double-angle) map carries $\\tan\\theta=x$ to $\\tan 2\\theta=\\dfrac{2x}{1-x^{2}}$. Evaluate the EXACT value of the angle \\[ \\Phi \\;=\\; 2\\,\\arctan\\!\\big(\\sqrt{2}+1\\big). \\] A classmate writes: \"Set $x=\\sqrt2+1$. Then $1-x^{2}=1-(3+2\\sqrt2)=-2-2\\sqrt2$ and $2x=2\\sqrt2+2$, so $\\dfrac{2x}{1-x^{2}}=\\dfrac{2\\sqrt2+2}{-2\\sqrt2-2}=-1$. Hence $\\Phi=2\\arctan x=\\arctan\\!\\big(\\tfrac{2x}{1-x^{2}}\\big)=\\arctan(-1)=-\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}.$\" Decide whether $\\Phi=-\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}$ is correct, and give the exact value of $\\Phi$ with a proof that locates it relative to $\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$.",
