          "Locate $\\theta=\\arctan(\\sqrt2+1)$ first. Since $\\sqrt2+1>1=\\tan\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}$ and $\\arctan$ is increasing, $\\theta>\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}$; and $\\theta<\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$ always. Hence $\\theta\\in\\left(\\tfrac{\\pi}{4},\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}\\right)$, so the double $\\Phi=2\\theta\\in\\left(\\tfrac{\\pi}{2},\\pi\\right)$: the doubled angle is genuinely obtuse, sitting in QII above the right angle.",
          "Compute its tangent by the Mobius map: $\\tan\\Phi=\\dfrac{2x}{1-x^{2}}$ with $x=\\sqrt2+1$. Then $x^{2}=3+2\\sqrt2$, $1-x^{2}=-2-2\\sqrt2$, $2x=2+2\\sqrt2$, so $\\tan\\Phi=\\dfrac{2+2\\sqrt2}{-2-2\\sqrt2}=-1$. This is a true statement about $\\tan\\Phi$ only — it does not name $\\Phi$.",
          "Now use the quadrant. In $\\left(\\tfrac{\\pi}{2},\\pi\\right)$ the unique angle with tangent $-1$ is $\\pi-\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}=\\tfrac{3\\pi}{4}$ (the QIV solution $-\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}$ is excluded because $\\Phi$ is obtuse). Therefore $\\Phi=\\boxed{\\dfrac{3\\pi}{4}}$, and the classmate's $-\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}$ is wrong by exactly $\\pi$ — the overshoot past $\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$ that $\\arctan$ could never have returned."
