    "remark": "The deceit lives entirely in one suppressed condition: $2\\arctan x=\\arctan\\!\\big(\\tfrac{2x}{1-x^{2}}\\big)$ is a CONDITIONAL identity, valid only on $|x|<1$, and acquires a $\\pi$ correction outside that window — $+\\pi$ for $x>1$ and $-\\pi$ for $x<-1$ — precisely so that the right-hand $\\arctan$ stays inside its mandated range $\\left(-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2},\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}\\right)$ while the left side is free to be obtuse. The Mobius map $x\\mapsto\\tfrac{2x}{1-x^{2}}$ is faithful to the TANGENT (which is $\\pi$-periodic, hence blind to the wrap) but unfaithful to the ANGLE the moment $2\\arctan x$ crosses $\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$, which happens exactly when $|x|>1$. The surd $\\sqrt2+1=\\tan\\tfrac{3\\pi}{8}$ is engineered so that doubling lands on $\\tfrac{3\\pi}{4}$ and the formula spits out the clean-looking $-1$, masking the fact that the angle has already wrapped. Top-rank discipline: whenever you push $\\arctan x$ (or $\\arcsin$, $\\arccos$) through a doubling, halving, or summing and then 'cancel' it against tan/sin/cos, the cancellation is licensed only while the resulting angle stays inside the inverse function's principal range — compute $\\tan\\Phi$ if you must, but earn the quadrant by an inequality before you commit to the value."
