    "statement": "Throughout use the standard principal branches \\[ \\sec^{-1}t=\\arccos\\!\\tfrac{1}{t}\\in[0,\\pi]\\setminus\\{\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}\\},\\qquad \\csc^{-1}t=\\arcsin\\!\\tfrac{1}{t}\\in\\left[-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2},\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}\\right]\\setminus\\{0\\}, \\] each defined exactly on $|t|\\ge 1$. Recall the reciprocal-inverse cofunction identity: on the whole common domain $|t|\\ge1$, $\\sec^{-1}t+\\csc^{-1}t=\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$ — a sum that lands precisely on the value $\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$ that neither summand is ever allowed to take by itself ($\\sec^{-1}$ skips $\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$, $\\csc^{-1}$ skips $0$). Determine every real $a$ for which \\[ \\csc^{-1}(a)-\\sec^{-1}(a)=\\frac{\\pi}{6}. \\] A student attacks it by taking the cosine of the difference: with $s=\\sec^{-1}a,\\ c=\\csc^{-1}a$, they write $\\cos(c-s)=\\cos c\\cos s+\\sin c\\sin s=\\cos\\tfrac{\\pi}{6}$, substitute $\\cos s=\\tfrac1a,\\ \\sin c=\\tfrac1a,\\ \\sin s=\\sqrt{1-\\tfrac1{a^{2}}},\\ \\cos c=\\sqrt{1-\\tfrac1{a^{2}}}$, reduce to $\\tfrac{2}{a}\\sqrt{1-\\tfrac1{a^{2}}}=\\tfrac{\\sqrt3}{2}$, and conclude that BOTH $a=\\tfrac{2}{\\sqrt3}$ and $a=2$ are solutions. Exactly one is genuine. Find it, and explain precisely why the other is a phantom.",
