    "remark": "Reciprocal inverses hide a deliberate asymmetry that this problem weaponises: their SUM is rigid ($\\sec^{-1}+\\csc^{-1}\\equiv\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$, magically landing on the one value each is individually forbidden to reach), but their DIFFERENCE is a free variable with a sign that depends on the branch. A solver who reflexively reaches for $\\cos(c-s)$ to 'symmetrise' the equation throws away exactly the information the problem is testing — cosine is even, so it cannot tell $+\\tfrac{\\pi}{6}$ from $-\\tfrac{\\pi}{6}$, and the phantom $a=2$ (the genuine root of the mirror equation) walks straight in. The disciplined move is to add the cofunction identity as a second linear equation and solve directly, or to bound $\\csc^{-1}a-\\sec^{-1}a$ branch-by-branch and notice it is negative on all of $a\\le-1$. Top-rank lesson: when a relation forces you onto $\\sec^{-1}/\\csc^{-1}$, exploit the sum identity to linearise, and never let an even function ($\\cos$, squaring) adjudicate an equation whose answer carries a sign."
