    "statement": "For every real number $x$, define \\[ f(x)=\\sin\\!\\left(\\,2\\arctan x-\\arccos\\frac{1-x^{2}}{1+x^{2}}\\,\\right). \\] Reduce $f$ to a single closed-form expression in $x$ that is correct on the whole real line, taking care that the second arccosine is not simply the negative of the first arctangent. State the result as an explicit (necessarily piecewise) function of $x$.",
    "answer": "\\[\\boxed{f(x)=\\begin{cases}0,& x\\ge 0\\\\ \\dfrac{4x\\,(1-x^{2})}{(1+x^{2})^{2}},& x<0\\end{cases}}\\]",
    "trap": "The seductive move is to write $\\arccos\\dfrac{1-x^{2}}{1+x^{2}}=2\\arctan x$, cancel it against the leading $2\\arctan x$, and conclude $f\\equiv\\sin 0=0$ for all $x$. But $\\arccos$ returns a value in $[0,\\pi]$, so $\\arccos\\dfrac{1-x^{2}}{1+x^{2}}=2\\arctan|x|$, not $2\\arctan x$. The two agree only when $x\\ge 0$. For $x<0$ the second term equals $-2\\arctan x$, so the inner angle is $2\\arctan x-(-2\\arctan x)=4\\arctan x$, not $0$, and $f$ is a genuine non-zero curve there. The cancellation is real on the right half-line and a mirage on the left.",
