        "name": "Sign-aware reduction via $\\arccos\\frac{1-x^2}{1+x^2}=2\\arctan|x|$",
        "steps": [
          "Put $\\theta=\\arctan x\\in(-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2},\\tfrac{\\pi}{2})$, so $\\tan\\theta=x$. Then $\\cos 2\\theta=\\dfrac{1-\\tan^2\\theta}{1+\\tan^2\\theta}=\\dfrac{1-x^2}{1+x^2}$. The number $2\\theta$ lies in $(-\\pi,\\pi)$, but $\\arccos$ must return a value in $[0,\\pi]$, so $\\arccos\\dfrac{1-x^2}{1+x^2}=|2\\theta|=2\\arctan|x|$.",
          "Hence the inner angle is $A(x)=2\\arctan x-2\\arctan|x|$. For $x\\ge 0$, $|x|=x$ gives $A=0$ and $f=\\sin 0=0$. For $x<0$, $|x|=-x$ gives $A=2\\arctan x-2\\arctan(-x)=4\\arctan x$, so $f=\\sin(4\\arctan x)$.",
          "Expand the left branch with double angles: $\\sin(4\\theta)=2\\sin 2\\theta\\cos 2\\theta$ where $\\sin 2\\theta=\\dfrac{2x}{1+x^2}$, $\\cos 2\\theta=\\dfrac{1-x^2}{1+x^2}$. Multiplying, $f(x)=2\\cdot\\dfrac{2x}{1+x^2}\\cdot\\dfrac{1-x^2}{1+x^2}=\\dfrac{4x(1-x^2)}{(1+x^2)^2}$ for $x<0$, while $f\\equiv 0$ for $x\\ge 0$, which is the boxed piecewise answer."
        ]
