          "By definition of $\\arccos$, $\\cos\\beta=\\dfrac{1-x^2}{1+x^2}$ and $\\sin\\beta=+\\sqrt{1-\\cos^2\\beta}=\\Big|\\dfrac{2x}{1+x^2}\\Big|=\\dfrac{2|x|}{1+x^2}$ (the sine of an arccos is never negative — this is exactly where the sign enters). Substituting, $f=\\dfrac{2x}{1+x^2}\\cdot\\dfrac{1-x^2}{1+x^2}-\\dfrac{1-x^2}{1+x^2}\\cdot\\dfrac{2|x|}{1+x^2}=\\dfrac{2(1-x^2)\\,(x-|x|)}{(1+x^2)^2}$.",
          "Now $x-|x|=0$ for $x\\ge 0$ (giving $f=0$) and $x-|x|=2x$ for $x<0$ (giving $f=\\dfrac{2(1-x^2)\\cdot 2x}{(1+x^2)^2}=\\dfrac{4x(1-x^2)}{(1+x^2)^2}$). This reproduces the boxed piecewise form, the $|x|$ being the lone carrier of the asymmetry."
