    "remark": "The whole problem turns on one inviolable fact: $\\arccos$ lands in $[0,\\pi]$, so $\\arccos\\frac{1-x^2}{1+x^2}=2\\arctan|x|$, not $2\\arctan x$. The leading $2\\arctan x$ is odd, the arccosine term is even, and their difference can only cancel where the two coincide — the right half-line. On the left half-line the inner angle quietly doubles to $4\\arctan x$, turning a trivially-zero claim into the nontrivial curve $\\frac{4x(1-x^2)}{(1+x^2)^2}$, whose value sweeps from $0$ down to $-1$ (at $x=1-\\sqrt2$) back to $0$ (at $x=-1$) up to $+1$ (at $x=-1-\\sqrt2$) and back to $0$. Whenever you see $\\sin$, $\\cos$, or $\\arccos$ of a half-angle-looking surd, ask which half-plane you are standing in before you cancel."
