    "trap": "The fatal habit is reading $[-1,1]$ off the symbols and stopping. The outer functions force their ARGUMENTS into $[-1,1]$, and those arguments are themselves $\\cos^{-1}x$ and $\\sin^{-1}x$, not $x$. Two extra constraints are hidden: (1) for $\\sin^{-1}(\\cos^{-1}x)$ one needs $-1\\le\\cos^{-1}x\\le1$, but $\\cos^{-1}x\\ge0$ always, so this collapses to $0\\le\\cos^{-1}x\\le1$, i.e. $\\cos 1\\le x\\le1$ — a cutoff at the irrational $x=\\cos1\\approx0.540$, never at $\\pm1$; (2) for $\\cos^{-1}(\\sin^{-1}x)$ one needs $-1\\le\\sin^{-1}x\\le1$, i.e. $-\\sin1\\le x\\le\\sin1$. Intersecting $[\\cos1,1]$ with $[-\\sin1,\\sin1]$ gives $[\\cos1,\\sin1]$, an asymmetric window roughly $[0.540,\\,0.841]$ whose BOTH endpoints are transcendental. A student who never folds in the $\\cos^{-1}x\\ge0$ fact, or who assumes symmetry about $0$, lands on $[-1,1]$ or $[-\\sin1,\\sin1]$ and accepts forbidden points such as $x=0$.",
