          "Term 2, $\\cos^{-1}(\\sin^{-1}x)$: the outer $\\cos^{-1}$ requires $\\sin^{-1}x\\in[-1,1]$, with $\\sin^{-1}x$ itself needing $x\\in[-1,1]$. Since $\\sin^{-1}$ is strictly increasing, $-1\\le\\sin^{-1}x\\le1\\iff \\sin(-1)\\le x\\le\\sin1\\iff -\\sin1\\le x\\le\\sin1$. Because $\\sin1\\approx0.841<1$, this interval $[-\\sin1,\\sin1]$ already sits inside $[-1,1]$, so term 2 is defined exactly on $[-\\sin1,\\,\\sin1]$.",
          "The sum is defined where both terms are, so $\\operatorname{dom}F=[\\cos1,1]\\cap[-\\sin1,\\sin1]$. Numerically $\\cos1\\approx0.540$ and $\\sin1\\approx0.841<1$, and $-\\sin1<\\cos1$, so the lower endpoint is $\\cos1$ and the upper is $\\sin1$: $\\operatorname{dom}F=\\boxed{[\\cos1,\\ \\sin1]}$. It is NOT symmetric about $0$ (its centre is $\\tfrac{\\cos1+\\sin1}{2}>0$), and both endpoints are transcendental, refuting the $[-1,1]$ claim."
