    "statement": "Let $g:[-1,1]\\to\\mathbb{R}$ be defined by \\[g(x)=\\bigl(\\sin^{-1}x\\bigr)\\,\\bigl(\\cos^{-1}x\\bigr),\\] the ordinary product of the two principal inverse-trig values. Find the exact range of $g$, and state the value of $x$ at which the maximum is attained and the value of $x$ at which the minimum is attained.",
    "answer": "\\[\\boxed{\\ \\Bigl[-\\tfrac{\\pi^{2}}{2},\\ \\tfrac{\\pi^{2}}{16}\\Bigr]\\ }\\]",
    "trap": "Writing $s=\\sin^{-1}x$ and using $\\cos^{-1}x=\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}-s$, the product becomes $\\phi(s)=s\\bigl(\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}-s\\bigr)$, a downward parabola. The seductive mistake is to forget that $x$ runs over the FULL interval $[-1,1]$, so $s=\\sin^{-1}x$ runs over $[-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2},\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}]$ — not $[0,\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}]$. A student who silently treats both factors as nonnegative (or mentally restricts $s\\ge 0$ because $\\cos^{-1}$ is) optimizes $\\phi$ only on $[0,\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}]$: there the maximum $\\tfrac{\\pi^{2}}{16}$ at $s=\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}$ is correct, but the minimum is wrongly read as $\\phi(0)=\\phi(\\tfrac{\\pi}{2})=0$, giving the bogus range $[0,\\tfrac{\\pi^{2}}{16}]$. In truth, for $x\\in[-1,0)$ we have $s<0$ while $\\cos^{-1}x>\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$, so the product turns NEGATIVE and dives. On the genuine $s$-interval the minimum sits at the LEFT endpoint $s=-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$ (i.e. $x=-1$), where $g(-1)=\\bigl(-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}\\bigr)(\\pi)=-\\tfrac{\\pi^{2}}{2}$ — far below $0$. Unlike a squared-sum, the product opens downward, so the max is interior and the min is forced to the (negative) endpoint, reversing the usual logic.",
    "solutions": [
      {
        "name": "Complementary substitution to a parabola in $s$",
        "steps": [
          "Put $s=\\sin^{-1}x$. As $x$ ranges over $[-1,1]$, $s$ ranges over the closed interval $\\bigl[-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2},\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}\\bigr]$ (this is the principal range of $\\sin^{-1}$, attained surjectively). Using $\\sin^{-1}x+\\cos^{-1}x=\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$ for all $x\\in[-1,1]$, we get $\\cos^{-1}x=\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}-s$, hence $g=\\phi(s)=s\\bigl(\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}-s\\bigr)=\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}s-s^{2}$.",
          "Now optimize the downward parabola $\\phi$ on the WHOLE interval $\\bigl[-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2},\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}\\bigr]$. Its vertex is at $s^{*}=\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}$, which lies inside the interval, giving the maximum $\\phi\\!\\bigl(\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}\\bigr)=\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}\\cdot\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}=\\tfrac{\\pi^{2}}{16}$. Because the parabola opens downward, the minimum is at an endpoint: compare $\\phi\\!\\bigl(-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}\\bigr)=\\bigl(-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}\\bigr)\\pi=-\\tfrac{\\pi^{2}}{2}$ against $\\phi\\!\\bigl(\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}\\bigr)=\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}\\cdot 0=0$; the smaller is $-\\tfrac{\\pi^{2}}{2}$ at the left endpoint $s=-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$.",
          "Since $\\phi$ is continuous and $s\\mapsto x=\\sin s$ is a continuous bijection of the interval, $g$ attains every value between its min and max. The maximum $\\tfrac{\\pi^{2}}{16}$ occurs at $s=\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}\\Rightarrow x=\\sin\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}=\\tfrac{1}{\\sqrt2}$, and the minimum $-\\tfrac{\\pi^{2}}{2}$ at $s=-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}\\Rightarrow x=-1$. Therefore the range is $\\boxed{\\bigl[-\\tfrac{\\pi^{2}}{2},\\,\\tfrac{\\pi^{2}}{16}\\bigr]}$."
        ]
      },
      {
        "name": "AM-GM/symmetric framing on the sum $s+c=\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$",
        "steps": [
          "Let $s=\\sin^{-1}x,\\ c=\\cos^{-1}x$, so $s+c=\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$ is a fixed constant while the pair varies. With fixed sum $\\Sigma=\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$, the product $sc$ is governed by the identity $sc=\\dfrac{\\Sigma^{2}-(s-c)^{2}}{4}=\\dfrac{\\pi^{2}/4-(s-c)^{2}}{4}$. So $g$ is a strictly decreasing function of $|s-c|$: maximal when $s-c$ is smallest in magnitude, minimal when $|s-c|$ is largest.",
          "The difference $s-c=\\sin^{-1}x-\\cos^{-1}x=2\\sin^{-1}x-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$ ranges over $\\bigl[2(-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2})-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2},\\,2(\\tfrac{\\pi}{2})-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}\\bigr]=\\bigl[-\\tfrac{3\\pi}{2},\\,\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}\\bigr]$. Thus $|s-c|$ attains its minimum $0$ (at $x=\\tfrac{1}{\\sqrt2}$, where $s=c=\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}$) and its maximum $\\tfrac{3\\pi}{2}$ (at $x=-1$, where $s-c=-\\tfrac{3\\pi}{2}$).",
          "Substituting the extreme values of $(s-c)^{2}$: maximum $g=\\dfrac{\\pi^{2}/4-0}{4}=\\tfrac{\\pi^{2}}{16}$ and minimum $g=\\dfrac{\\pi^{2}/4-9\\pi^{2}/4}{4}=\\dfrac{-2\\pi^{2}}{4}=-\\tfrac{\\pi^{2}}{2}$. By continuity the intermediate values are all hit, so the range is $\\boxed{\\bigl[-\\tfrac{\\pi^{2}}{2},\\,\\tfrac{\\pi^{2}}{16}\\bigr]}$, with max at $x=\\tfrac{1}{\\sqrt2}$ and min at $x=-1$."
        ]
      },
      {
        "name": "Calculus on $x$ directly, with endpoint check",
        "steps": [
          "Differentiate $g(x)=\\sin^{-1}x\\,\\cos^{-1}x$ on $(-1,1)$: $g'(x)=\\dfrac{\\cos^{-1}x}{\\sqrt{1-x^{2}}}+\\sin^{-1}x\\cdot\\Bigl(-\\dfrac{1}{\\sqrt{1-x^{2}}}\\Bigr)=\\dfrac{\\cos^{-1}x-\\sin^{-1}x}{\\sqrt{1-x^{2}}}$. Setting $g'(x)=0$ gives $\\cos^{-1}x=\\sin^{-1}x$, and with their sum $\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$ this forces $\\sin^{-1}x=\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}$, i.e. $x=\\tfrac{1}{\\sqrt2}$ — the only interior critical point.",
          "The numerator $\\cos^{-1}x-\\sin^{-1}x=\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}-2\\sin^{-1}x$ is positive for $x<\\tfrac{1}{\\sqrt2}$ and negative for $x>\\tfrac{1}{\\sqrt2}$, so $g$ increases then decreases: $x=\\tfrac{1}{\\sqrt2}$ is the global maximum, with $g\\!\\bigl(\\tfrac{1}{\\sqrt2}\\bigr)=\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}\\cdot\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}=\\tfrac{\\pi^{2}}{16}$.",
          "The minimum must therefore be at an endpoint of $[-1,1]$. Evaluate: $g(1)=\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}\\cdot 0=0$ and $g(-1)=\\bigl(-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}\\bigr)\\cdot\\pi=-\\tfrac{\\pi^{2}}{2}$. The minimum is the smaller, $-\\tfrac{\\pi^{2}}{2}$ at $x=-1$. As $g$ is continuous on the connected domain, the range is the full interval $\\boxed{\\bigl[-\\tfrac{\\pi^{2}}{2},\\,\\tfrac{\\pi^{2}}{16}\\bigr]}$."
        ]
      }
    ],
    "remark": "Two complementary angles with a fixed sum tempt you to recall the schoolbook fact that a product with fixed sum is maximized when the factors are equal — true here, giving the neat interior max $\\tfrac{\\pi^{2}}{16}$ at $x=\\tfrac{1}{\\sqrt2}$. But the inverse-trig context hides a sign: because $\\sin^{-1}$ reaches $-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$ while $\\cos^{-1}$ stays in $[0,\\pi]$, the product is not pinned to nonnegative values — at $x=-1$ it plunges to $-\\tfrac{\\pi^{2}}{2}$, the true floor. The minimum is therefore an endpoint phenomenon driven by the negative branch of $\\sin^{-1}$, not the symmetric interior point. This is the mirror image of the squared-sum problem $(\\sin^{-1}x)^{2}+(\\cos^{-1}x)^{2}$, which opens upward and pushes its extremum the opposite way: there the interior point gives the min, here it gives the max."
