          "Therefore $f=\\sin^{-1}(g)$ with $g$ sweeping all of $[-1,1]$. Since $\\sin^{-1}$ is a continuous bijection from $[-1,1]$ onto $\\left[-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2},\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}\\right]$, the image of $f$ is exactly $\\sin^{-1}\\!\\bigl([-1,1]\\bigr)=\\left[-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2},\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}\\right]$. This already refutes the claimed $[-\\pi,\\pi]$: no value of $\\sin^{-1}$ can exceed $\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$.",
          "The maximum $\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$ occurs where $g=1$, i.e. $4x^{2}(1-x^{2})=1\\Rightarrow(2x^{2}-1)^{2}=0\\Rightarrow x^{2}=\\tfrac12$; on $[-1,1]$ the largest $f$ is at $x=\\tfrac{1}{\\sqrt2}$. The fold points of the closed form are exactly where $g$ peaks/troughs, namely $x=\\pm\\tfrac1{\\sqrt2}$, beyond which $g$ decreases and $\\sin^{-1}$ runs back down. Thus $\\boxed{\\operatorname{Range}f=\\left[-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2},\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}\\right],\\ \\text{folds at }x=\\pm\\tfrac1{\\sqrt2}}$."
