          "The factor $\\operatorname{sgn}(1-2x^{2})$ flips sign exactly at $x=\\pm\\tfrac1{\\sqrt2}$: $f'>0$ for $|x|<\\tfrac1{\\sqrt2}$ and $f'<0$ for $|x|>\\tfrac1{\\sqrt2}$. These sign changes are the fold points; the closed form has corners there (the appearance of $|1-2x^{2}|$ is precisely the branch fold the naive cancellation hides).",
          "So $f$ increases on $\\left[-\\tfrac1{\\sqrt2},\\tfrac1{\\sqrt2}\\right]$ and decreases on the two outer pieces. The candidate extreme values are at the critical abscissae and the endpoints: $f(\\pm\\tfrac1{\\sqrt2})=\\sin^{-1}(\\pm1)=\\pm\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$, while $f(\\pm1)=\\sin^{-1}0=0$ and $f(0)=0$. The global maximum is $\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$ at $x=\\tfrac1{\\sqrt2}$ and minimum $-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$ at $x=-\\tfrac1{\\sqrt2}$, giving $\\boxed{\\operatorname{Range}f=\\left[-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2},\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}\\right]}$ with folds at $x=\\pm\\tfrac1{\\sqrt2}$."
