    "remark": "The shape is a symmetric tent that overshoots and turns over: from $x=-1$ to $x=1$ the graph goes $0\\to-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}\\to0\\to\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}\\to0$, with both peaks pinned at $\\pm\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$ at the fold abscissae $x=\\pm\\tfrac1{\\sqrt2}$ and a return to $0$ at the endpoints $x=\\pm1$. The fatal shortcut is cancelling $\\sin^{-1}\\!\\bigl(\\sin(2\\sin^{-1}x)\\bigr)$ to $2\\sin^{-1}x$ without checking that $2\\sin^{-1}x$ stays inside the principal window $\\left[-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2},\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}\\right]$. The cleanest sanity check needs no algebra at all: an $\\sin^{-1}$ output is permanently caged in $\\left[-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2},\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}\\right]$, so any answer claiming a range like $[-\\pi,\\pi]$ is wrong before you compute a single value."
