    "statement": "A smooth-looking curve is traced for the parameter $t\\in\\mathbb{R}$ by \\[ x(t)=\\sin^{-1}\\!\\left(\\frac{2t}{1+t^{2}}\\right),\\qquad y(t)=\\tan^{-1}\\!\\left(\\frac{3t-t^{3}}{1-3t^{2}}\\right), \\] with the principal branches $\\sin^{-1}u\\in\\left[-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2},\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}\\right]$ and $\\tan^{-1}v\\in\\left(-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2},\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}\\right)$. A confident student substitutes $t=\\tan\\theta$, writes $x=2\\theta$ and $y=3\\theta$, hence $x=2\\tan^{-1}t$, $y=3\\tan^{-1}t$, and concludes $\\dfrac{dy}{dx}=\\dfrac{3}{2}$ for every $t$. Find the EXACT value of $\\dfrac{dy}{dx}$ at $t=2$, and determine the full sign behaviour of $\\dfrac{dy}{dx}$ as $t$ ranges over $\\mathbb{R}\\setminus\\{0\\}$.",
    "answer": "\\[\\boxed{\\ \\left.\\frac{dy}{dx}\\right|_{t=2}=-\\frac{3}{2},\\qquad \\frac{dy}{dx}=\\frac{3}{2}\\,\\operatorname{sgn}\\!\\left(1-t^{2}\\right)\\ }\\]",
    "trap": "Both inner arguments are genuine multiple-angle forms: with $t=\\tan\\theta$ and $\\theta=\\tan^{-1}t\\in\\left(-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2},\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}\\right)$ they become $\\dfrac{2t}{1+t^{2}}=\\sin 2\\theta$ and $\\dfrac{3t-t^{3}}{1-3t^{2}}=\\tan 3\\theta$. The fatal step is collapsing $\\sin^{-1}(\\sin 2\\theta)\\to 2\\theta$ and $\\tan^{-1}(\\tan 3\\theta)\\to 3\\theta$ as if both held everywhere. They do not — and crucially the branch correction is DIFFERENT for the two pieces. For $x$: $\\sin^{-1}(\\sin 2\\theta)=2\\theta$ only while $2\\theta\\in\\left[-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2},\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}\\right]$, i.e. $|\\theta|\\le\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}$, i.e. $|t|\\le 1$; once $|t|>1$ it FOLDS to $\\pi-2\\theta$ (or $-\\pi-2\\theta$), so $\\dfrac{dx}{dt}$ switches sign at $|t|=1$. For $y$: $\\tan^{-1}(\\tan 3\\theta)$ only JUMPS by integer multiples of $\\pi$ at $|t|=\\tfrac{1}{\\sqrt3},\\sqrt3$, and a jump does not alter the slope between jumps, so $\\dfrac{dy}{dt}=\\dfrac{3}{1+t^{2}}$ has CONSTANT sign. Because the fold lives only in $x(t)$ and not in $y(t)$, the ratio $\\dfrac{dy}{dx}$ flips sign at $|t|=1$. The naive answer $\\tfrac{3}{2}$ has the WRONG sign for all $|t|>1$ — in particular at $t=2$ the true slope is $-\\tfrac{3}{2}$, not $+\\tfrac{3}{2}$.",
    "solutions": [
      {
        "name": "Honest chain rule, keeping the absolute value",
        "steps": [
          "Differentiate each piece without simplifying. For $x$, let $u=\\dfrac{2t}{1+t^{2}}$; then $1-u^{2}=\\dfrac{(1-t^{2})^{2}}{(1+t^{2})^{2}}$, so $\\sqrt{1-u^{2}}=\\dfrac{|1-t^{2}|}{1+t^{2}}$, and $u'=\\dfrac{2(1-t^{2})}{(1+t^{2})^{2}}$ gives $\\dfrac{dx}{dt}=\\dfrac{u'}{\\sqrt{1-u^{2}}}=\\dfrac{2(1-t^{2})}{(1+t^{2})\\,|1-t^{2}|}=\\dfrac{2\\,\\operatorname{sgn}(1-t^{2})}{1+t^{2}}.$ The $|1-t^{2}|$ — not a cancelled $(1-t^{2})$ — is exactly the fold the student dropped.",
          "For $y$, let $v=\\dfrac{3t-t^{3}}{1-3t^{2}}$. A direct quotient differentiation (or recognising $\\tfrac{d}{dt}\\tan^{-1}(\\tan 3\\theta)=3\\,\\theta'$ between jumps) yields $\\dfrac{dy}{dt}=\\dfrac{3}{1+t^{2}}$, valid for all $t$ except the jump abscissae $t=\\pm\\tfrac{1}{\\sqrt3},\\pm\\sqrt3$; its sign never changes.",
          "Divide: $\\dfrac{dy}{dx}=\\dfrac{dy/dt}{dx/dt}=\\dfrac{3/(1+t^{2})}{2\\,\\operatorname{sgn}(1-t^{2})/(1+t^{2})}=\\dfrac{3}{2}\\,\\operatorname{sgn}(1-t^{2}),$ since $\\operatorname{sgn}(1-t^{2})^{-1}=\\operatorname{sgn}(1-t^{2})$. Thus $\\dfrac{dy}{dx}=+\\tfrac{3}{2}$ for $|t|<1$ and $-\\tfrac{3}{2}$ for $|t|>1$. At $t=2$ this is $\\boxed{-\\tfrac{3}{2}}$."
        ]
      },
      {
        "name": "Trig substitution with explicit branch resolution",
        "steps": [
          "Put $t=\\tan\\theta$, $\\theta=\\tan^{-1}t\\in\\left(-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2},\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}\\right)$, so $\\tfrac{d\\theta}{dt}=\\tfrac{1}{1+t^{2}}>0$. Then $x=\\sin^{-1}(\\sin 2\\theta)$ and $y=\\tan^{-1}(\\tan 3\\theta)$. Resolve $x$ on the principal $\\sin^{-1}$ window: $x=2\\theta$ when $|\\theta|\\le\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}$ (that is $|t|\\le 1$), but $x=\\pi-2\\theta$ for $\\theta\\in\\left(\\tfrac{\\pi}{4},\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}\\right)$ (that is $t>1$) and $x=-\\pi-2\\theta$ for $\\theta\\in\\left(-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2},-\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}\\right)$ (that is $t<-1$).",
          "Hence $\\dfrac{dx}{d\\theta}=+2$ on $|t|<1$ and $-2$ on $|t|>1$, i.e. $\\dfrac{dx}{d\\theta}=2\\,\\operatorname{sgn}(1-t^{2})$. For $y$, the relation $y=\\tan^{-1}(\\tan 3\\theta)=3\\theta-k\\pi$ holds with the integer $k$ constant between the jump points $3\\theta=\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}+m\\pi$ (i.e. $t=\\pm\\tfrac{1}{\\sqrt3},\\pm\\sqrt3$); subtracting a constant does not change the derivative, so $\\dfrac{dy}{d\\theta}=3$ throughout.",
          "Therefore $\\dfrac{dy}{dx}=\\dfrac{dy/d\\theta}{dx/d\\theta}=\\dfrac{3}{2\\,\\operatorname{sgn}(1-t^{2})}=\\dfrac{3}{2}\\,\\operatorname{sgn}(1-t^{2}).$ At $t=2$ we have $|t|>1$, so the slope is $\\boxed{-\\tfrac{3}{2}}$; for $|t|<1$ it is $+\\tfrac{3}{2}$."
        ]
      },
      {
        "name": "Geometric reading of the two graphs",
        "steps": [
          "Track $x(t)$ as $t$ increases from $0$: the argument $\\tfrac{2t}{1+t^{2}}$ rises to its maximum $1$ at $t=1$ then falls, so $x$ climbs from $0$ to $\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$ on $(0,1)$ and DESCENDS back toward $0$ on $(1,\\infty)$ — a tent with apex at $t=1$. So $x$ is increasing in $t$ for $|t|<1$ and decreasing for $|t|>1$: $\\operatorname{sgn}\\!\\left(\\tfrac{dx}{dt}\\right)=\\operatorname{sgn}(1-t^{2})$.",
          "Track $y(t)$: $\\tan^{-1}(\\tan 3\\theta)$ is a sawtooth in $\\theta=\\tan^{-1}t$ with slope $+3$ on every tooth and vertical drops of $\\pi$ at the breakpoints. Away from those isolated jumps $y$ is strictly increasing in $t$, so $\\dfrac{dy}{dt}>0$ with magnitude $\\tfrac{3}{1+t^{2}}$ for all admissible $t$ — the breaks never reverse the local rise.",
          "The slope $\\dfrac{dy}{dx}$ is the ratio of these rates; since only $x$ reverses direction (at $t=\\pm1$) while $y$ keeps the same orientation, the curve doubles back on itself there and the tangent's sign flips. Magnitude $\\left|\\dfrac{dy}{dx}\\right|=\\dfrac{3/(1+t^{2})}{2/(1+t^{2})}=\\dfrac{3}{2}$ everywhere it exists, with sign $\\operatorname{sgn}(1-t^{2})$. At $t=2$, $\\dfrac{dy}{dx}=\\boxed{-\\tfrac{3}{2}}$."
        ]
      }
    ],
    "remark": "The whole problem is a stress test of one habit: never cancel $\\sin^{-1}(\\sin\\cdot)$ or $\\tan^{-1}(\\tan\\cdot)$ without locating the branch. The deeper lesson here is that the two inverse functions correct DIFFERENTLY. An $\\sin^{-1}$ overshoot produces a FOLD (the closed form changes slope, so $\\tfrac{dx}{dt}$ flips sign), whereas a $\\tan^{-1}$ overshoot produces only a JUMP (a constant $\\pm\\pi$ shift that leaves $\\tfrac{dy}{dt}$ untouched). Because the fold lives in $x(t)$ alone, the parametric slope reverses at $|t|=1$ even though the point on the curve moves continuously — the curve retraces its $x$-extent while $y$ marches on. The naive $\\tfrac{3}{2}$ is right in magnitude and right for $|t|<1$, but carries the wrong sign on the entire outer region $|t|>1$."
