    "statement": "Let \\[ F(x)=\\tan^{-1}\\!\\left(\\frac{\\cos x-\\sin x}{\\cos x+\\sin x}\\right),\\qquad \\tan^{-1}\\in\\left(-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2},\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}\\right), \\] defined on $\\left[\\tfrac{\\pi}{2},\\pi\\right]$ except where the denominator vanishes. Define the two numbers \\[ I=\\int_{\\pi/2}^{\\pi}F'(x)\\,dx\\qquad\\text{and}\\qquad D=F(\\pi)-F\\!\\left(\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}\\right), \\] where $I$ is the genuine integral of the derivative $F'$ over the interval (the isolated point where $F'$ fails to exist has measure zero and does not affect the integral). A student differentiates and finds $F'(x)=-1$ for all $x$, then writes $I=\\int_{\\pi/2}^{\\pi}(-1)\\,dx=-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$ and invokes the Fundamental Theorem to declare $D=I=-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$. Find the ordered pair $(I,\\,D)$, and identify the exact size and location of the defect that makes $D\\neq I$.",
    "answer": "\\[\\boxed{(I,\\,D)=\\left(-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2},\\ \\tfrac{\\pi}{2}\\right)}\\]",
    "trap": "The differentiation is correct: writing $\\dfrac{\\cos x-\\sin x}{\\cos x+\\sin x}=\\dfrac{1-\\tan x}{1+\\tan x}=\\tan\\!\\left(\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}-x\\right)$ gives $F(x)=\\tan^{-1}\\!\\big(\\tan(\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}-x)\\big)$, and indeed $F'(x)=-1$ at every point where $F$ is differentiable. So $I=-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$ is right. The fatal move is the NEXT line: applying the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus as if $F$ were an antiderivative valid throughout $\\left[\\tfrac{\\pi}{2},\\pi\\right]$. It is not — $F$ has a JUMP DISCONTINUITY at $x=\\tfrac{3\\pi}{4}$, exactly where $\\cos x+\\sin x=0$, i.e. where $\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}-x$ crosses $-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$ and the principal $\\tan^{-1}$ snaps up by $\\pi$. The FTC in the form $\\int_a^b F'=F(b)-F(a)$ requires $F$ to be continuous on $[a,b]$; here $F$ is not, so the two sides legitimately differ. Tracking the branch, $F(x)=\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}-x$ on $\\left[\\tfrac{\\pi}{2},\\tfrac{3\\pi}{4}\\right)$ and $F(x)=\\tfrac{5\\pi}{4}-x$ on $\\left(\\tfrac{3\\pi}{4},\\pi\\right]$, so $D=F(\\pi)-F(\\tfrac{\\pi}{2})=\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}-(-\\tfrac{\\pi}{4})=+\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$, NOT $-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$. The slope $-1$ never lied; the student lost the single upward jump of height $\\pi$ that the integral of $F'$ simply cannot see.",
    "solutions": [
      {
        "name": "Resolve the branch into two continuous pieces",
        "steps": [
          "Simplify the argument: $\\dfrac{\\cos x-\\sin x}{\\cos x+\\sin x}=\\dfrac{1-\\tan x}{1+\\tan x}=\\tan\\!\\left(\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}-x\\right)$, so $F(x)=\\tan^{-1}\\!\\big(\\tan(\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}-x)\\big)$. The principal value equals $\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}-x$ only while $\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}-x\\in\\left(-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2},\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}\\right)$, i.e. $x\\in\\left(-\\tfrac{\\pi}{4},\\tfrac{3\\pi}{4}\\right)$. Thus on $\\left[\\tfrac{\\pi}{2},\\tfrac{3\\pi}{4}\\right)$ we have $F(x)=\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}-x$.",
          "For $x\\in\\left(\\tfrac{3\\pi}{4},\\pi\\right]$ the angle $\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}-x$ has dropped below $-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$, so we add $\\pi$ to return to the principal window: $F(x)=\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}-x+\\pi=\\tfrac{5\\pi}{4}-x$. Both pieces have slope $-1$, confirming $F'(x)=-1$ where it exists and hence $I=\\int_{\\pi/2}^{\\pi}(-1)\\,dx=-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$.",
          "Now read off the endpoints from the correct pieces: $F\\!\\left(\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}\\right)=\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}=-\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}$ and $F(\\pi)=\\tfrac{5\\pi}{4}-\\pi=\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}$, so $D=\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}-\\left(-\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}\\right)=\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$. Hence $(I,D)=\\left(-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2},\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}\\right)$, and the gap $D-I=\\pi$ is precisely the upward jump of $F$ at $x=\\tfrac{3\\pi}{4}$. $\\boxed{(I,D)=\\left(-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2},\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}\\right)}$"
        ]
      },
      {
        "name": "Jump-corrected Fundamental Theorem",
        "steps": [
          "Split the endpoint difference at the single discontinuity $c=\\tfrac{3\\pi}{4}$ and add and subtract the one-sided limits: $D=F(\\pi)-F(\\tfrac{\\pi}{2})=\\big[F(\\pi)-F(c^{+})\\big]+\\big[F(c^{+})-F(c^{-})\\big]+\\big[F(c^{-})-F(\\tfrac{\\pi}{2})\\big].$ On each of the two open subintervals $F$ IS a continuous antiderivative of $F'=-1$, so the genuine FTC applies there.",
          "The two continuous brackets are honest integrals of $F'$: $F(c^{-})-F(\\tfrac{\\pi}{2})=\\int_{\\pi/2}^{c}(-1)\\,dx$ and $F(\\pi)-F(c^{+})=\\int_{c}^{\\pi}(-1)\\,dx$; together they give $\\int_{\\pi/2}^{\\pi}F'\\,dx=I=-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$. The middle bracket is the jump $J=F(c^{+})-F(c^{-})$. Since near $c$ the principal $\\tan^{-1}$ leaps from $-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$ to $+\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$, $J=\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}-\\left(-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}\\right)=+\\pi$.",
          "Therefore $D=I+J=-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}+\\pi=\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$. The corrected statement $\\,D=\\int_a^bF'+\\sum(\\text{jumps in }(a,b))\\,$ shows exactly why the naive FTC failed: it omitted the lone $+\\pi$ jump at $\\tfrac{3\\pi}{4}$. $\\boxed{(I,D)=\\left(-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2},\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}\\right)}$"
        ]
      },
      {
        "name": "Direct definite integral, integrand untouched",
        "steps": [
          "Compute $I$ from $F'$ without any branch talk. With $u=\\tan\\!\\left(\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}-x\\right)$, $F=\\tan^{-1}u$ gives $F'=\\dfrac{u'}{1+u^{2}}$ where $u'=-\\sec^{2}\\!\\left(\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}-x\\right)$ and $1+u^{2}=\\sec^{2}\\!\\left(\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}-x\\right)$, so $F'(x)=-1$ identically (away from $x=\\tfrac{3\\pi}{4}$, where $u\\to\\pm\\infty$). The single bad point has measure zero, so $I=\\int_{\\pi/2}^{\\pi}(-1)\\,dx=-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$.",
          "Compute $D$ straight from the defining formula, NOT from $I$. At $x=\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$: $\\dfrac{\\cos-\\sin}{\\cos+\\sin}=\\dfrac{0-1}{0+1}=-1$, so $F(\\tfrac{\\pi}{2})=\\tan^{-1}(-1)=-\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}$. At $x=\\pi$: $\\dfrac{-1-0}{-1+0}=1$, so $F(\\pi)=\\tan^{-1}(1)=\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}$.",
          "Hence $D=\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}-\\left(-\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}\\right)=\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$, while $I=-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$. The two are computed by independent, fully valid routes and genuinely disagree by $\\pi$ — a calculus-level proof that $F$ cannot be a continuous antiderivative on $\\left[\\tfrac{\\pi}{2},\\pi\\right]$. $\\boxed{(I,D)=\\left(-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2},\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}\\right)}$"
        ]
      }
    ],
    "remark": "This is the integral mirror of the more familiar slope-trap: there, naively cancelling an inverse-trig branch gives a wrong piecewise derivative; here the derivative is flawlessly $-1$, yet the Fundamental Theorem still detonates. The reason is structural — $\\int_a^bF'=F(b)-F(a)$ is a theorem about CONTINUOUS $F$, and $F(x)=\\tan^{-1}\\!\\big(\\tan(\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}-x)\\big)$ carries a built-in jump of $+\\pi$ at $x=\\tfrac{3\\pi}{4}$ that no integral of the (a.e.) derivative can detect. The clean bookkeeping is $F(b)-F(a)=\\int_a^bF'(x)\\,dx+\\sum_{c\\in(a,b)}\\big(F(c^{+})-F(c^{-})\\big)$; the sawtooth's vertical risers are invisible to the slope but fully visible to the endpoint difference. A top student should reflexively ask, before writing FTC, where the antiderivative jumps — and count the jumps inside the limits."
