    "statement": "With the principal branch $\\sec^{-1}t\\in[0,\\pi]\\setminus\\{\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}\\}$ (so that $\\sec^{-1}t=\\cos^{-1}(1/t)$ for $t\\ge 1$), and the principal branch $\\sin^{-1}u\\in[-\\tfrac{\\pi}{2},\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}]$, define for $x>1$ \\[ g(x)\\;=\\;\\sec^{-1}(x)\\;-\\;\\sin^{-1}\\!\\bigl(\\sqrt{2(x-1)}\\,\\bigr). \\] At $x=1$ the graph $y=\\sec^{-1}(x)$ rises with a vertical tangent, and the subtracted arcsine is engineered to absorb that same vertical rise. Find \\[ L\\;=\\;\\lim_{x\\to 1^{+}}\\frac{g(x)}{(x-1)^{3/2}}. \\] A hurried student, declaring the form $0/0$, applies L'Hopital and on the side claims that since the limit \"clearly exists as a number it must also be approachable from the left,\" so the two-sided limit equals $L$ as well. Compute $L$, and decide whether the two-sided limit $\\lim_{x\\to 1}\\dfrac{g(x)}{(x-1)^{3/2}}$ exists.",
    "answer": "\\[\\boxed{\\,L=-\\dfrac{3\\sqrt{2}}{4}\\,}\\]",
    "trap": "Two false moves lurk. First, the DOMAIN/ONE-SIDEDNESS trap: $\\sec^{-1}(x)$ needs $x\\ge 1$ (its argument $1/x$ must lie in $[-1,1]$ from the $x\\ge1$ side) and $\\sqrt{2(x-1)}$ is real only for $x\\ge1$, so $g$ is not even defined for $x<1$. The two-sided limit therefore cannot exist no matter how nice $L$ is; the blow-up of $\\sec^{-1}$ at $x=1$ is a vertical tangent, an intrinsically one-sided phenomenon. Declaring \"the number exists so the two-sided limit equals it\" is the conceptual error. Second, the ORDER trap: both terms behave like $\\sqrt{2}\\,\\sqrt{x-1}$, so a student who cancels leading terms and reports the difference of leading coefficients gets $0$, or who stops after one careless L'Hopital without controlling the $\\sqrt{x^2-1}$ factor mishandles the $(x-1)^{3/2}$ order and loses the genuine next coefficient $-\\tfrac{3\\sqrt2}{4}$.",
