          "Bound the sum honestly. Each term satisfies $\\tan^{-1}k>\\tan^{-1}1=\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}$ for $k\\ge3$, so the sum exceeds $4\\cdot\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}=\\pi$; and each term is $<\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$, so the sum is $<4\\cdot\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}=2\\pi$. Thus the sum lies strictly in $(\\pi,2\\pi)$.",
          "The only value of the form $-\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}+k\\pi$ inside $(\\pi,2\\pi)$ is $k=2$, i.e. $\\dfrac{7\\pi}{4}$. (Equivalently $k=2$ counts the two crossings of $ab>1$ recorded by the overflow law.) Hence the sum is $\\boxed{\\dfrac{7\\pi}{4}}$."
